{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Botswana", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Botswana}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Botswana\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Botswana]]\n| first_case = [[Gaborone]]\n| arrival_date = 30 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]] via UK and Thailand\n| recovery_cases = 0\n| deaths = 1\n| confirmed_cases = 6\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nThis article documents the impacts of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in [[Botswana]], and may not include all the contemporary major responses and measures.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019. This cluster was initially linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in Wuhan City. However, some of those first cases with laboratory confirmed results had no link to the market, and the source of the epidemic is unknown.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref>\n\nUnlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> COVID-19 typically appears with about seven days of [[Influenza-like illness|flu-like symptoms]] followed by some people progressing to symptoms of a [[viral pneumonia]] requiring admission to hospital.<ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> From 19 March, COVID-19 was no longer classified as a \"High consequence infectious disease\".<ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\" />\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 30 March, the first three cases in the country were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Botswana registers first Covid-19 cases as three people test positive|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/botswana-registers-first-covid-19-cases-as-three-people-test-positive-45797335|website=www.iol.co.za|date=2020-03-31|accessdate=2020-03-31|language=en|last=|publisher=}}</ref> On 25 March a 78-year-old woman who was suspected of having [[COVID-19]] died in [[Ramotswa]]. A few days after her death, the results came back positive making it the fourth case of COVID-19 in Botswana. In a live broadcast on [[Botswana TV|BTV]] vice president [[Slumber Tsogwane|Tsogwane]] said tracer teams had picked up 14 other people who had been in contact with the deceased and testing has been conducted on them. Results are pending as of April 1.\n\n==Prevention==\nAs a precautionary measure the government has banned gatherings of more than 50 people and the entry of people from countries deemed high-risk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmegi.bw/index.php?aid=84896&dir=2020/march/16|title=Coronavirus: Botswana bans US, UK, China arrivals,All learning institutions to be closed on the 23rd March 2020|date=17 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/botswana-bars-travellers-from-coronavirus-hit-countries/|title=Botswana bars travellers from coronavirus-hit countries|date=16 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> On March 24, the government announced that borders would be closed. Citizens of Botswana are permitted to return but must be quarantined for 14 days. There is concern, however, that people may still enter Botswana illegally from [[Zimbabwe]] by avoiding official border crossings.<ref>{{cite news |title=Botswana, with No COVID-19 Cases, Closes Borders After Death in Zimbabwe {{!}} Voice of America - English |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/botswana-no-covid-19-cases-closes-borders-after-death-zimbabwe |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=www.voanews.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe pandemic and travel restrictions disrupted what was to be Botswana's first [[elephant hunting]] season since 2014<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus may mean Botswana's hunting season is cancelled |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-botswana-hunting-season-cancelled-200324063714759.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> and affected the [[diamond]] industry.<ref>{{cite news |title=Botswana's Diamond Sales Face Slump as Coronavirus Locks Out Key Buyers {{!}} Voice of America - English |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/botswanas-diamond-sales-face-slump-coronavirus-locks-out-key |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=www.voanews.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn the 31st of March the president of Botswana, [[Mokgweetsi Masisi]] gave a speech and declared a State of Public Emergency for the purpose of taking appropriate and stringent measures to address the risks posed by the [[COVID-19 pandemic]]. The president said that a 21-day State of Public Emergency would not be sufficient to employ the necessary measures to fight the pandemic. The State of Public Emergency would come into effect from Thursday, 2 April 2020 00:00 GMT+2 until Thursday, 30 April 2020 00:00 GMT+2. The full presidential response can be found here: [https://drive.google.com/open?id=1SMuG_sIy5Aw8sb5W6t3kOxOzV1mGH1lE Botswana's response to the COVID-19 pandemic]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Botswana|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Botswana]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Botswana]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Botswana]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Botswana}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Botswana\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Botswana]]\n| first_case = [[Gaborone]]\n| arrival_date = 30 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]] via UK and Thailand\n| recovery_cases = 0\n| deaths = 1\n| confirmed_cases = 6\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nThis article documents the impacts of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in [[Botswana]], and may not include all the contemporary major responses and measures.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019. This cluster was initially linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in Wuhan City. However, some of those first cases with laboratory confirmed results had no link to the market, and the source of the epidemic is unknown.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref>\n\nUnlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> COVID-19 typically appears with about seven days of [[Influenza-like illness|flu-like symptoms]] followed by some people progressing to symptoms of a [[viral pneumonia]] requiring admission to hospital.<ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> From 19 March, COVID-19 was no longer classified as a \"High consequence infectious disease\".<ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\" />\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 30 March, the first three cases in the country were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Botswana registers first Covid-19 cases as three people test positive|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/botswana-registers-first-covid-19-cases-as-three-people-test-positive-45797335|website=www.iol.co.za|date=2020-03-31|accessdate=2020-03-31|language=en|last=|publisher=}}</ref> On 25 March a 78-year-old woman who was suspected of having [[COVID-19]] died in [[Ramotswa]]. A few days after her death, the results came back positive making it the fourth case of COVID-19 in Botswana. In a live broadcast on [[Botswana TV|BTV]] vice president [[Slumber Tsogwane|Tsogwane]] said tracer teams had picked up 14 other people who had been in contact with the deceased and testing has been conducted on them. Results are pending as of April 1.\n\n==Prevention==\nAs a precautionary measure the government has banned gatherings of more than 50 people and the entry of people from countries deemed high-risk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmegi.bw/index.php?aid=84896&dir=2020/march/16|title=Coronavirus: Botswana bans US, UK, China arrivals,All learning institutions to be closed on the 23rd March 2020|date=17 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/botswana-bars-travellers-from-coronavirus-hit-countries/|title=Botswana bars travellers from coronavirus-hit countries|date=16 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> On March 24, the government announced that borders would be closed. Citizens of Botswana are permitted to return but must be quarantined for 14 days. There is concern, however, that people may still enter Botswana illegally from [[Zimbabwe]] by avoiding official border crossings.<ref>{{cite news |title=Botswana, with No COVID-19 Cases, Closes Borders After Death in Zimbabwe {{!}} Voice of America - English |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/botswana-no-covid-19-cases-closes-borders-after-death-zimbabwe |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=www.voanews.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe pandemic and travel restrictions disrupted what was to be Botswana's first [[elephant hunting]] season since 2014<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus may mean Botswana's hunting season is cancelled |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-botswana-hunting-season-cancelled-200324063714759.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> and affected the [[diamond]] industry.<ref>{{cite news |title=Botswana's Diamond Sales Face Slump as Coronavirus Locks Out Key Buyers {{!}} Voice of America - English |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/botswanas-diamond-sales-face-slump-coronavirus-locks-out-key |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=www.voanews.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn the 31st of March the president of Botswana, [[Mokgweetsi Masisi]] gave a speech and declared a State of Public Emergency for the purpose of taking appropriate and stringent measures to address the risks posed by the [[COVID-19 pandemic]]. The president said that a 21-day State of Public Emergency would not be sufficient to employ the necessary measures to fight the pandemic. The State of Public Emergency would come into effect from Thursday, 2 April 2020 00:00 GMT+2 until Thursday, 30 April 2020 00:00 GMT+2. The full presidential response can be found here: [https://drive.google.com/open?id=1SMuG_sIy5Aw8sb5W6t3kOxOzV1mGH1lE Botswana's response to the COVID-19 pandemic]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Botswana|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Botswana]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Botswana]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Botswana]]\n\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n{{Botswana-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Botswana"}
{"title_page": "Lee Fierro", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n'''Elizabeth Lee Fierro'''<ref name=weiss20/> (February 13, 1929 \u2013 April 5, 2020) was an American actress best known for playing Mrs. Kintner  in the ''[[Jaws_(franchise)|Jaws]]'' film franchise. She lived for many years on [[Martha's Vineyard]], where from 1974 to 2017 she was artistic director of the Island Theatre Workshop.<ref name=vg17>{{cite news |title=Three Cheers, Bon Voyage for Lee Fierro |url=https://vineyardgazette.com/news/2017/06/01/three-cheers-bon-voyage-lee-fierro |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=[[Vineyard Gazette]] |date=1 June 2017 |language=en}}</ref> She died on April 5,<ref name=seemayer20>{{cite news |last1=Seemayer |first1=Zach |title=Lee Fierro, 'Jaws' Actress, Dies of Coronavirus Complications at 91 |url=https://www.etonline.com/lee-fierro-jaws-actress-dies-of-coronavirus-complications-at-91-144274 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=[[Entertainment Tonight]] |date=5 April 2020}}</ref> 2020 of [[COVID-19]].<ref name=\"brennan20\">{{cite news |last1=Brennan |first1=George |title=Lee Fierro, \u2018fiercely dedicated\u2019 to theater, has died |url=https://www.mvtimes.com/2020/04/05/lee-fierro-fiercely-dedicated-theater-died/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=[[The Martha's Vineyard Times]] |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=alexander20>{{cite news |last1=Alexander |first1=Bryan |title='Jaws' actress Lee Fierro, whose Mrs. Kintner slapped Chief Brody, dies of coronavirus at 91 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/movies/2020/04/05/jaws-actress-lee-fierro-mrs-kintner-slaps-chief-brody-dies/2952350001/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=moreau20>{{cite news |last1=Moreau |first1=Jordan |title=Lee Fierro, \u2018Jaws\u2019 Actor, Dies of Coronavirus at 91 |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/lee-fierro-jaws-dead-dies-coronavirus-1234571541/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=5 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=weiss20>{{cite news |last1=Weiss |first1=Josh |title=Lee Fierro, Mrs. Kintner is Steven Spielberg's 'Jaws,' dies at 91 from coronavirus complications |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/lee-fierro-mrs-kintner-in-jaws-dies-at-91 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=SYFY WIRE |date=5 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 she received a \"Woman of the Year\" award by Women Empowered to Make Healthy Choices for her local theater workshop.<ref name=teawithlee17>{{cite news |title=Farewell \u201cTea with Lee\u201d for Lee Fierro |url=https://www.mvtimes.com/2017/05/31/farewell-tea-lee-lee-fierro/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=[[The Martha's Vineyard Times]] |date=31 May 2017}}</ref> \nHer famous ''Jaws'' scene required several \"takes\".<ref name=garrett14>{{cite news |last1=Garrett |first1=Major |title=40 years later \"Jaws\" still alive on Martha's Vineyard |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/40-years-later-jaws-still-alive-on-marthas-vineyard/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=www.cbsnews.com |date=1 September 2014 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]'' (1975)\n*''[[Jaws: The Revenge]]'' (1987)\n*''The Mistover Tale'' (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0276444}}\n\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n'''Elizabeth Lee Fierro'''<ref name=weiss20/> (February 13, 1929 \u2013 April 5, 2020) was an American actress best known for playing Mrs. Kintner  in the ''[[Jaws_(franchise)|Jaws]]'' film franchise. She lived for many years on [[Martha's Vineyard]], where from 1974 to 2017 she was artistic director of the Island Theatre Workshop.<ref name=vg17>{{cite news |title=Three Cheers, Bon Voyage for Lee Fierro |url=https://vineyardgazette.com/news/2017/06/01/three-cheers-bon-voyage-lee-fierro |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=[[Vineyard Gazette]] |